<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-755-143  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 755 143.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  July 17 1989 v10 n28 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bankruptcy courts automate cases.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mahnke, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Federal bankruptcy courts are implementing a decentralizedUnix-based system of minicomputers and 80386-based processors toautomate case processing and handle rising case levels withoutadding staff.andP;  The Bankruptcy Court Automation Project is a highpriority of the Administrative Office of the US Courts, anaffiliate of the Federal Judicial Center, which developed thesystem.andP;  At the same time, courts in the 94 federal districts arealso working on ways to handle rising caseloads and reduce thenumber of court appearances required by attorneys and the public.andO;In Boston, one of the first districts to implement the computersystem, a new DEC information system featuring acomputer-generated voice allows the public to call in about caseinformation.andP;  Also in Boston, attorneys will be able to use theirminicomputers to get case status and other information from themain bankruptcy computer system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BankruptcyAutomationInformation ProcessingCourtsNational GovernmentMinicomputersUnited States. Federal Judicial CenterUnited States. Administrative Office of the United States CourtsMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>